            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "I feel that it can be worked around like browser does with blobs. Whenever you need to show custom bytes in an `<img>` element, you need to somehow pass these bytes there.\n\nHow a browser handles it is that  there is an API for `URL.createObjectURL(bytes)` which creates a link like `blob://domain-name/uuid` that basically points to a locally saved copy of bytes.\n\nProposed approach:\n\n**Phase 1**\n\nSomething that can be done to make clients (and not nvim) care about streaming is to save copies of files to `/tmp/` or wherever and give URLs to clients. Clients read from the provided URL, but this URL is considered to be an opaqie id (so it should not be inspected by clients).\n\n**Phase 2**\n\nProvide API to stream these URLs from the disk copies. Something like `vim.blob.read(id)`. Deprecate contract that clients might read this URL directly.\n\n**Phase 3**\n\nOnce some time passed, **stop saving copies on disk** and instead stream underlying data directly from the source.\n\n---\n\nThat's a consumer pipeline, something like that could be done for producers. I can elaborate more if it's something interesting.",
